did.abstract: Collection includes meeting minutes, correspondence, newsletters, and files with subjects of importance to the residents of Burleith. The collection also includes material about the social activities sponsored by the Burleith Citizens Association such as a neighborhood flea market and art show.

bioghist.head: Historical or Biographical Note
bioghist.p: The Burleith Citizens Association (BCA) began in 1925 with the adoption of a constitution. The modern history of the Burleith neighborhood began in 1886 when the Huidekoper family came into possession of the Burleith tract. The family built some homes and filled in a large hole at the corner of present day S and 37th streets. Much of the tract remained fields and woods when, in 1922, the Huidekoper family sold the tract to Shannon and Luchs, Inc. Shannon and Luchs, using a consulting architect, designed homes that they marketed to people with moderate income, but above average taste. These homes have an American Colonial architecture style. Many have slate mansard roofs and dormer windows. The homes were priced between $8,950-$13,500. The Burleith neighborhood is located next to Georgetown. The Burleith Citizens Association's articles of incorporation state that the goal of the organization is to ". . . engage in the promotion of the common good and general welfare of the people of Burleith through activities designated to bring about civic betterment and social improvement." In its efforts to achieve this goal, the BCA participates in many activities and monitors issues important to the community including parking, traffic light installation, noise pollution, and the community's relationship with its neighbor, Georgetown University. These civic activities are complimented by social activities including picnics, an annual flea market, and activities specifically for children including an Easter egg hunt and Halloween party.

scopecontent.head: Collection Scope and Content
scopecontent.p: The BCA collection includes meeting minutes, correspondence, newsletters, and files with subjects of importance to the residents of Burleith. The collection also includes material about the social activities sponsored by the BCA such as a neighborhood flea market and art show. In 1973, Burleith celebrated its 50th Anniversary and the material collected for that event constitutes the bulk of the early history of Burleith. This history comes from correspondence and interviews with former residents and the family members of early landowners and promotional materials distributed by Shannon and Luchs, Inc. The Burleith community's major growth began in 1922 when Shannon and Luchs, Inc. purchased a significant portion of the Burleith tract. Shannon and Luchs built most of the 540 homes in Burleith's four-block area. The collection is divided into eleven series based on either the type of material and subject. Within each series the folders are arranged either chronologically or alphabetically by folder title.

arrangement.head: Collection Organization
arrangement.p: Organized into fourteen series: Activities/Events; Administrative Files; Committees; Correspondence; Graphics; History; Membership; Minutes; Newsletters; Subject files; Ephemera; 2003 Accretion: Correspondence; 2003 Accretion: Minutes; 2003 Accretion: Subject files

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents note
scopecontent.p: This series contains information for many of the social events BCA participated in and/or sponsored including the annual dinner, flea market, and picnics. For many of these events the information is brief consisting of only a folder or two. For other events, such as the art show and the Burleith 50th Anniversary celebration, there is more documentation and a researcher may get a more complete history of these events.

scopecontent.p: The administrative files series is a sample of the operational materials produced by the organization. This material includes Treasurers' reports and by-laws and articles of incorporation. For additional Treasurer's reports researchers should use the Minutes Series.

scopecontent.p: The BCA committees represented here are not all the committees within BCA, but do represent a wide range of topics including zoning, service and safety, playground, and Georgetown University.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents note
scopecontent.p: The correspondence includes outgoing letters that primarily state BCA positions on various issues and perhaps request support and assistance. For example, a letter to the principal of Western High School requesting the use of part of the high school's grounds during the BCA art show. Other series in the collection have correspondence. These two folders arrived with correspondence as their folder designation and therefore Special Collection staff kept them separate. It is possible that some of the topics within these two folders match topics within the Subject Files Series.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents note
scopecontent.p: The images in this series are a random sampling of various activities such as the children's Halloween party and images of the neighborhood around Burleith including Georgetown University and Western High School. The folders in other series that have images also have documents. The graphics folders have only images.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents note
scopecontent.p: This series has materials about the history of the Burleith neighborhood including a brief history written by a resident and promotional material published by Shannon and Luchs, Inc. The material in this series is not a history of BCA. There are also a few blueprints of a Shannon and Luchs house.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents note
scopecontent.p: The folders in this series are divided by street addresses. Most folders contain a list compiled by the block captains that summarize the addresses for members and the dues paid. The folders also contain the actual membership applications. These applications contain the name of the household members both adult and children and often includes the occupation of the household members and the relationship between the adults in the house.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents note
scopecontent.p: The BCA newsletters (name change to the Burleith Bell in October 2004) in this series cover the dates 1960 to 2018.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents note
scopecontent.p: This series includes a wide range of topics from D.C. Federation of Civic Associations to Duke Ellington School and the Hillandale development. All the subjects are important to the BCA and represent issues they worked on or in some way associated with. One of the more interesting subjects in this series is the real estate covenant for Burleith. These include the original covenants and the indentures written to maintain the covenants when after they were set to expire. The material within these subject files may also help researchers understand Burleith's history such as the boundaries maps.
